node.text: Mad Genius and F&W Culinary Director at Large @justinchapple ushers in fall flavors and end-of-summer vibes with his Pork Chops with Three-Apple Slaw recipe. Seared chops and fresh mix of sweet and tart apples—Granny Smith,Honeycrisp, and Gala—get tossed in a creamy, poppy seed-laced dressing for freshness and a crunchy pop of flavor. Tap the link in bio for the recipe!

node.text: This Plum Galette from Chef Jacques Pépin is a rustic tart with an elegant finish. The buttery, flaky pâte brisée dough gets filled with fresh, seasonal fruit and baked until richly browned in the oven. A final brushing of fruit preserves provides flavorful and beautiful sheen. Tap the link in bio for the recipe!

node.text: The inspiration for this Spicy Tofu and Zucchini Stew that @annie.h.shi makes for cozy weeknight dinners every season of the year comes from Soondubu Jjigae, a spicy Korean tofu stew, that she grew up eating at restaurants. The recipe features an umami-rich broth powered by dashi packets, gochugaru, doenjang (fermented soybean paste), and gochujang. Tap the link in bio for the recipe!

node.text: “I think this cookie is so elegant and so New York chic and I’m gonna take it to SoHo,” says Chef Paola Velez (@smallorchids) as she adds gold leaf to her take on the classic Black and White cookie. Bling aside, these Black and Ruby Cookies are already extra special with ruby chocolate instead of white, buttermilk instead of whole, and rye flour as a nod to iconic NYC deli breads. Find out how to make them by visiting this link:https://bit.ly/3zD88fk or tap the link in bio for the recipe!

node.title: Pastries with Paola | Black and Ruby Cookies

Kubaneh Toast with Brown Sugar Ricotta and Berries from F&W 2020 Best New Chef @camillecogswell features a sweet, golden brown traditional Yemenite Sabbath bread with homemade ricotta. Great for breakfast, a morning snack or a weekend project, the caramel notes of the recipe make this one a sweet keeper. Tap the link in bio for the recipe! 
📸: @taradonnephoto

node.text: We’re so happy to have had the opportunity to celebrate our Food & Wine Classic in person once again. After a long time of not seeing each other, it was so wonderful to spend time together and do what we do best, talk food and wine! Thanks to Lexus Culinary Master Stephanie Izard (@stephanieizard) for teaching us how to make her Skirt Steak Lettuce Wraps (and not one but three amazing cocktails). #Sponsored #LexusCulinary 📸: @galdophoto

node.text: Mad Genius and F&W Culinary Director at Large @justinchapple ushers in fall flavors and end-of-summer vibes with his Pork Chops with Three-Apple Slaw recipe. Seared chops and fresh mix of sweet and tart apples—Granny Smith,Honeycrisp, and Gala—get tossed in a creamy, poppy seed-laced dressing for freshness and a crunchy pop of flavor. Tap the link in bio for the recipe!

node.text: Are you ready to master the spatchcocked chicken? What about sushi rice? We asked some of our favorite chefs around the country for the one thing that every home cook should know how to make. From simple dishes like scrambled eggs to hearty meals like pasta bolognese, find out what homework they're giving you through the link in bio. 📸: @conpoulos_photographer

node.text: On this episode of Chefs At Home, sommelier Derrick C. Westbrook (@derrickcwestbrook) makes Lobster Frites and pairs it with Chablis. Garlic butter-poached lobster gets drizzled with an Old Bay aioli on top of twice-fried French fried potatoes. Westbrook says the preparation is "taking something soulful and old and giving it a new lift." Tap the link in bio to watch the full episode on YouTube!

node.text: Our 2021 class of Best New Chefs is finally here! Representing the Midwest and South, we have chefs Fermin Nunez, Ji Hye Kim, Trey Smith, and Blake Aguillard. Fermín Núñez (@chiefnunez) is advancing a new definition of Tex-Mex cooking through fresh masa and spreading the gospel of great tortillas. Ji Hye Kim (@jihyekim__) offers lessons in the history of Korean cuisine interspersed with memories of her mother's cooking and inspiration from Michigan ingredients. Meanwhile, Trey Smith and Blake Aguillard (@blakeaguillard_ @treysmithnola) are the duo behind one of the most accessible, creative, and ambitious menus in the nation. Meet these four Best New Chefs, along with the rest of the members of the 2021 class, through the link in bio. #FWBNC

node.text: Our 2021 class of Best New Chefs is finally here! Representing the East Coast we have chefs Angel Barreto, Lucas Sin and Paola Velez. Angel Barreto (@angellbarreto) is a lifelong student of Korean food who pushes boundaries with menus that look to both past and future for inspiration. Lucas Sin (@lucas.sin) is on a mission to take a delicious deep dive into changing the perception of American Chinese food with an eye toward sustainability when it comes to people, their mental health and their finances. Meanwhile Paola Velez (@smallorchids) strives to improve kitchen culture and help make the hospitality industry a more fair and equitable place all while making by bold, vibrant desserts and maintaining an unmatched energy, humor and enthusiasm. Meet these three Best New Chefs, along with the rest of the members of the 2021 class, through the link in bio. #FWBNC

node.text: Our 2021 class of Best New Chefs is finally here! Representing the west coast we have chefs Carlo Lamagna, Gaby Maeda, Matt Horn, and Thessa Diadem. Matt horn (@matthornx) is a self-taught pit master who’s never worked in any restaurant but his own and is now solely dedicated to creating a unique, personal, and delicious style of barbecue. Gaby Maeda (@gmaeda25) is drawing inspiration from her Honolulu childhood to create a menu that is part Hawaiian, part Californian, and entirely her own. Meanwhile Thessa Diadem (@thessa.diadem) is getting inspired by the international grocery stores around her and channeling them into innovative, decadent pastries that look just as good as they taste. For Carlo Lamagna (@twistedfilipino) cooking is an homage to the vibrant flavors of his childhood in the Philippines as well as a tribute to his late father and community. Meet these four Best New Chefs, along with the rest of the members of the 2021 class, through the link in bio. #FWBNC
